with its appurtenances, and they being so seised made partition. William enfeoffed Thomas T hurneff of his part and Amery enfeoffed Robert Wyerne, the grandfather of the claimant. After the death of Robert Wyerne, William Wyerne, his son and heir, entered into one moiety of the manor, held it during his life, enjoyed the purparty of the profits as appurtenances thereto and died seised thereos. After his death the moiety of the manor with the purparty of the profits descended to the claimant as son and heir of William. Thus they are prepared to prove that they and all former holders of the manor from ancient time have had a. woodward in the wood and the bark of all such oaks.
